  "introduction": "**The Mystery of the Invisible Mix**: Ask students, 'If I give you a glass of water from this tap, is it pure H2O?' Let them discuss. Reveal that even clear water contains dissolved minerals and gases (a mixture). Then ask: 'How do we know if our measurement of its mass is accurate? Do we write 10g or 10.005g?' This sets the stage for why Significant Figures are crucial in chemistry.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Chemistry begins with defining matter and how to measure it accurately. Matter is classified into pure substances (elements/compounds) which have fixed composition, and mixtures which do not. Measurements must be reported using significant figures to reflect the precision of the instrument used.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Matter is anything that has mass and occupies space.",
      "Pure substances cannot be separated by physical means; mixtures can.",
      "Significant figures indicate the reliability of a measurement."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "**Classification**: Pure substances are divided into Elements (one type of atom) and Compounds (two or more elements in fixed ratio). Mixtures are Physical combinations. Homogeneous mixtures have uniform composition throughout (e.g., salt water), while Heterogeneous mixtures do not (e.g., sand and iron).\n\n**Measurement & Sig Figs**: In science, we never measure perfectly. We record all certain digits plus one uncertain digit.\n- **Rule 1**: Non-zero digits are always significant.\n- **Rule 2**: Zeros between non-zeros are significant.\n- **Rule 3**: Leading zeros (before the first non-zero) are NOT significant.\n- **Rule 4**: Trailing zeros in a number with a decimal point ARE significant. If no decimal, they may or may not be (ambiguous).\n\n**Example**: The mass of an object measured as 12.05 g has 4 significant figures. This tells us the balance was precise to at least two decimal places."
  },
