        "answer": "**Classification of Matter**:\nMatter is broadly classified into **Pure Substances** and **Mixtures**. Pure substances have a fixed composition and distinct properties (e.g., Gold, Water). Mixtures are physical combinations of components that retain their individual identities.\n\n**Types of Mixtures**:\n1. **Homogeneous Mixture**: These mixtures have a uniform composition throughout the sample. The components are not visibly distinguishable.\n   - *Examples*: Salt water, Air (gas mixture).\n2. **Heterogeneous Mixture**: These do not have a uniform composition; different parts may look or behave differently.\n   - *Examples*: Sand and iron filings, Oil and water.\n\n**Difference**: The key difference lies in the uniformity of composition and visibility of components.",
